ask: dpa_app sscanf %s width + sprintf -> snprintf (audit B6 / DA-01, DA-02)

AUDIT-dpa_app DA-01 + DA-02: dpa.c parses cdx_pcd.xml table names and
formats DPAA port names into bounded buffers using unsafe primitives.

DA-01 — sscanf("%s", ...) with no width specifier into info->name[64]:

  sscanf(tblname, "fm%d/port/%dG/%d/ccnode/%s",     ...)
  sscanf(tblname, "fm%d/port/OFFLINE/%d/ccnode/%s", ...)

`info->name` is char[64] (TABLE_NAME_SIZE in cdx_ioctl.h). The %s
specifier reads until whitespace with no length cap, so a hostile
or buggy PCD authoring tool emitting a >63-char ccnode tail
overflows the surrounding info struct on the stack of the dpa_app
caller. Fix: %s -> %63s on both call sites; the trailing NUL is
written by sscanf at offset 63, which exactly matches char[64].

DA-02 — sprintf into bounded port-name buffers:

  sprintf(port_info->name, "dpa-fman%d-oh@%d",   ...);   /* case 0 */
  sprintf(port_info->name, "dpa-fm%d-1G-eth%d",  ...);   /* case 1 */
  sprintf(port_info->name, "dpa-fm%d-10G-eth%d", ...);   /* case 2 */
  sprintf(name, "fm%d", finfo->index);                   /* x3 sites */

`port_info->name` is CDX_CTRL_PORT_NAME_LEN bytes (32 per the prior
audit) and `name` is char[256] local. With pathological u32 input
(`fm_index`/`port_id` near UINT_MAX), the rendered string can
exceed the destination — overflow by 1 byte in the worst case.
Fix: replace every sprintf(buf, ...) with snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), ...).

This converts both classes mechanically; no behaviour change on
the well-formed-input path. Truncation on hostile input is the
new safe failure mode.

Userspace-only — no kernel-side delta, no ABI/UAPI change.

